							  <h1>Amorepacific Headquarters, Yongsan, Seoul</h1>
								
							<a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/NN5kFYuLBtM4j1Lz6" target="_blank">
								  100, Hangang-daero, Yongsan-gu, Seoul, South Korea
								</a>
							  <p><em>Architect: David Chipperfield</em></p>
								

							  <p> 
								Located in Seoul’s Yongsan district, the Amorepacific headquarters goes beyond a typical corporate building — it’s a cultural space open to the public. Designed by British architect David Chipperfield, the building is inspired by the calm elegance of Korean moon jars, expressed in a modern cube form.
							  </p>
							  <p>
								Rather than directly referencing Korean design, Chipperfield focused on translating the essence of Korean aesthetics into architectural language. The result is a minimal, serene structure that plays with natural light and water to evoke emotion.
							  </p>
							  <p>
								At the heart of the building is a three-story atrium open to everyone. Unlike a traditional lobby, this space serves as a peaceful urban plaza, filled with soft daylight filtered through a skylight and a reflecting pool above.
							  </p>
							  <p>
								Inside the atrium you’ll find the Amorepacific Museum of Art, the apLAP design library, and the retro-futuristic Osulloc 1979 tea room, where scent, music, and storytelling blend to offer a full sensory experience.
							  </p>
							  <p>
								The building also houses a 450-seat hall (Amore Hall), an archive space that chronicles the company’s heritage, and the Amore Store, a curated showcase of all their beauty brands under one roof.
							  </p>
							  <p>
								What’s most unique is how accessible and inviting the space is, despite being a corporate HQ. Locals and travelers alike can naturally explore it, making it a rare case of a private building actively engaging with its city and community.
							  </p>
							</section>

